"Yesterday I had the most inspiring sight of my life-we played two shows. In the afternoon, the division in the mountains where we showed declared a half holiday and we had an audience of over 500
0 men. They sat on a mountainside and we played in an improvised stage with two, two and a half ton trucks on either side as dressing rooms and two other trucks with their lights on for spot lights. To see these men who had had nothing in the way of enter
t
ainment for weeks enjoy our show was worth the hardships we encountered to get there. And when we finished and played the Marsielles, God Save the King and the Star Spangled Banner and see 5000 dirty tired but happy soldiers stand at salute, it gave me a 
thrill I'll never forget. I'M doing some actual good sweetie, I can see it and feel it. The men after the show came up to me, the officers and G.I.'s and shook hands and told me how much they appreciated me bringing the show to them. The}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5654863 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9251421  haven't had a thing
 in the way of entertainment for weeks, some of them for months. We're a good trouping outfit-these French professionals I have are swell--take all kinds of hard living, traveling, bivouac tenting and kit eating with a smile and a laugh and say 'this is t
he least we can do'."--APO 512.
